    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Amoy.</placeName>
                    <date>28 March, 1866.</date>
                    <seg type="supplemental">Charles Darwin, Esq<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</seg>
                    <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>On returning to my post at Takow after a 10 day’s revel in the heart of the Formosan Mountains, I found orders awaiting me to repair to Amoy to relieve my brother-in-law M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Pedder who goes home by this mail.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> My sister, M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Pedder, has kindly offered to take home a small parcel for me.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> It occurred to me on her making this offer that I was under promise to procure for you some Chinese Honey-comb, or rather comb of the Chinese Honey-Bee.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> Enclosed in this box are several pieces of the article you desire, which my man procured after a long hunt through the town, this not being the season for gathering the honey— I hope you will be pleased with the present, and that you may find it to answer your purpose—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>If you have anything further that I can assist you in, do not fail to let me know of it. Now that I am in China <hi rend="underline">proper</hi> again &amp; once more within the line of regular communication I can the more easily procure any article you desire and find opportunities for forwarding such to you—</p>
<p>Your’s sincerely, | Robert Swinhoe.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Swinhoe was in the British diplomatic service in Takow, Formosa (now Taiwan), and Amoy, China (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3313.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">P. B. Hall 1987</ref>). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6506.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Henry Pedder</ref> was British consul in Amoy (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2609.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Foreign Office list</hi></ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Mrs Pedder has not been further identified.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The earlier correspondence between Swinhoe and CD about the comb of the Chinese honey-bee (<hi rend="italic">Apis indica</hi>) has not been found. Swinhoe may have previously sent CD a specimen of the honey-bee from Amoy (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 12, letter to Frederick Smith, [<hi rend="italic">c.</hi> 17 February 1864?] and n. 8).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">In 1863, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5233.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas White Woodbury</ref> had suggested to CD that it would be interesting to compare the size of the cells of <hi rend="italic">Apis indica</hi> with those in the combs of European species of honey-bee (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 11, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4049.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. W. Woodbury, 17 March 1863</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
